      "content": "Imagine the muscle fiber under a microscope as a tightly packed, slightly stressed bundle of protein filaments. When you apply intense mechanical tension, it's like a sudden, sharp tug on those filaments, causing some of them to fray or tear a little. The satellite cells, which are like tiny, dormant emergency repair crews clinging to the outside of these fibers, would then be seen actively migrating towards the damaged spots. They would then start to fuse with the torn areas, integrating their genetic material to help rebuild the frayed sections into stronger, thicker muscle tissue.",
